  <fr:p>The algebra structure is unique if it exists because <fr:tex>\mathbb {L}</fr:tex> is a Kock–Zöberlein monad, i.e. a monad for which the structure maps of algebras are left adjoint to the unit in the order-enrichment. Therefore, it suffices to show that there merely exists an algebra structure <fr:tex>{ \mathsf { L } {A} } \xrightarrow {{ \alpha }}{ A }</fr:tex> for any <fr:link
href="jms-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-001S">pointed</fr:link> dcpo <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>We define the structure map <fr:tex>\alpha</fr:tex> to take <fr:tex>u \in \mathsf { L } {A}</fr:tex> to the <fr:link
href="jms-001U.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-001U">supremum of the semidirected subset</fr:link> <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left \{ x \in  A  \mid  u =  \eta _Ax \right \} \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, so we may write <fr:tex>\alpha  u =  \bigsqcup _{p:u{ \downarrow }}u[p]</fr:tex>. It is not difficult to see that this assignment is continuous.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>The unit law for the algebra is trivial. The multiplication law is verified as follows:</fr:p>

  <fr:tex
display="block">\alpha { \mathopen {} \left ( \mathsf { L } { \alpha }  { \mathopen {} \left ( \phi ,u \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}    =  \alpha { \mathopen {} \left ( \phi ,  \alpha  u \right ) \mathclose {}}    =    \bigsqcup _{p:u{ \downarrow }}    \bigsqcup _{q:u[p]{ \downarrow }}   u[p][q]   =  \alpha { \mathopen {} \left ( \mu _A { \mathopen {} \left ( \phi ,u \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}    </fr:tex>
